<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06242051 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06242051 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  SAN-FRANCISCO; ADVERTISING; COMPANY; CONTRACT; AWARD  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Just five years ago, Goodby, Berlin andamp; Silverstein was little more than a smallSan Francisco ad agency, best known for creating San Francisco Examinercommercials that spoofed legendary publisher William Randolph Hearst.;   Manynational awards and clients later, the Bay Area shop is quickly becoming amajor industry force. Goodby, Berlin sealed its new-found status last week bywinning American Isuzu Motors Inc.'s coveted $92 million account -- one of thebiggest ad deals of the summer.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  S.F. AGENCY WINS ISUZU ACCOUNT  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The account will necessitate that Goodby, Berlin open a small Los Angelesoffice in order to be closer to City of Industry-based American Isuzu.;   TheIsuzu business brings the agency's annual billings to $250 million, up from$72 million last year. What's more, Goodby, Berlin has added clients at a timeof massive retrenchment in the advertising industry.;   Earlier this year, theagency won the Carl's Jr. Restaurants and New Yorker magazine accounts. Italso is doing work for Finlandia Vodka, the National Basketball Associationand Heinz Pet Products.;   &quot;We've always been self-confident about what wewanted to do,&quot; said partner Rich Silverstein.;   He credits the agency'ssuccess in tough times to efficient use of limited resources. &quot;When you don'thave much money to spend, your work better&quot; have an impact, he said.;  Silverstein, along with Berlin and Jeff Goodby, opened for business in 1983,working out of a 500-square-foot office with mismatched furniture.;   Today,the agency has 75 employees -- and plans to add about 30 more.;   All threeprincipals worked at Ogilvy andamp; Mather's San Francisco office and wanted toproduce campaigns that would &quot;cut through the clutter of mundane advertising,&quot;Silverstein said.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Los Angeles Daily News  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910829  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  August  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4F  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  276  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday, August 29, 199100242051,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>